---
import CourseLayout from '../../layouts/CourseLayout.astro';

const sections = [
  { id: 'fine-tuning', label: 'Fine-Tuning & Deployment' },
  { id: 'classification', label: 'Text Classification & Validation' },
];
---

<CourseLayout
  day={3}
  title="Deploying for Research"
  description="Fine-tuning, serving, and building rigorous text classification pipelines with proper validation for social science research."
  sections={sections}
>

  <!-- ===== FINE-TUNING ===== -->
  <section id="fine-tuning">
    <h2>Fine-Tuning &amp; Deployment</h2>
    <p>
      When prompting alone is insufficient&mdash;because your task is too
      specialized, your budget is limited, or you need full control over the
      model&mdash;fine-tuning lets you adapt a pretrained model to your specific
      needs.
    </p>

    <div class="definition-box">
      <p class="definition-box__label">Definition</p>
      <p class="definition-box__term">LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation)</p>
      <p>
        A parameter-efficient fine-tuning method that freezes the pretrained
        weights and injects trainable low-rank matrices into each layer. This
        reduces the number of trainable parameters by orders of magnitude while
        achieving performance comparable to full fine-tuning.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p>
      We also cover serving fine-tuned models: using vLLM for efficient local
      inference, working with API providers for batch processing, and the
      practical considerations of deploying models for large-scale text
      analysis.
    </p>

    <div class="key-takeaway">
      <p class="key-takeaway__label">Key Takeaway</p>
      <p>
        LoRA makes fine-tuning accessible on consumer hardware. Combined with
        efficient serving, this opens a path where social scientists can
        customize models for their specific annotation tasks rather than
        relying solely on general-purpose APIs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== TEXT CLASSIFICATION ===== -->
  <section id="classification">
    <h2>Text Classification &amp; Validation</h2>
    <p>
      Text classification is perhaps the most common application of LLMs in
      social science: sentiment analysis, topic labeling, stance detection,
      framing analysis. But using LLMs as annotators introduces new challenges
      around reliability and validity.
    </p>

    <p>
      We build complete classification pipelines: from prompt design through
      label aggregation to validation against human annotations. Key concepts
      include inter-annotator agreement metrics, stratified validation sets,
      and diagnosing systematic errors.
    </p>

    <div class="stop-and-think">
      <div class="stop-and-think__header">
        <svg class="stop-and-think__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
          <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/>
          <path d="M9.09 9a3 3 0 0 1 5.83 1c0 2-3 3-3 3"/>
          <line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/>
        </svg>
        <span class="stop-and-think__label">Stop and Think</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        You achieve 92% accuracy on your validation set using GPT-4 for
        sentiment classification of political tweets. Is this good enough to
        deploy for your full corpus of 500,000 tweets? What else would you check?
      </p>
      <details>
        <summary>Reveal</summary>
        <div>
          <p>
            Accuracy alone is insufficient. You should check: class balance in
            the validation set and corpus, per-class precision and recall (is it
            systematically miscategorizing one sentiment?), whether the
            validation set is representative of the full corpus, temporal
            stability, and cost at scale. A 92% accuracy with strong bias against
            minority classes could introduce systematic measurement error.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

</CourseLayout>
